      }
    },
    "methodology": {
      "title": "How this projection works",
      "intro": "The fan is a Monte Carlo simulation — it does not draw straight lines into the future. Instead it replays your own trading edge thousands of times and shows the range of plausible outcomes.",
      "step1_title": "Sample your history.",
      "step1_body": "Every closed trade in the filtered window contributes its R-multiple (profit/loss measured in units of risk).",
      "step2_title": "Estimate remaining trades.",
      "step2_body": "Your historical pace projects how many more trades remain until 31 December.",
      "step3_title": "Run N simulations.",
      "step3_body": "For each of 10,000 simulated years we draw that many R-multiples at random, with replacement, from your real distribution and accumulate them on top of today's total.",
      "step4_title": "Derive percentile bands.",
      "step4_body": "At each month-end we read the 10th, 25th, 50th, 75th and 90th percentiles across all simulations. The median is P50; the shaded P25–P75 and P10–P90 bands are the confidence intervals. They widen over time because uncertainty compounds with each additional trade.",
      "step5_title": "Read the answers.",
      "step5_body": "Goal probability is the share of simulations that finish at or above your goal. Risk of Ruin is the share that finish negative.",
      "disclaimer": "This is a model of your past behaviour, not a promise. It assumes future trades resemble past ones and ignores changes in market regime, position sizing or discipline."
    }
